  "id": "EXP-11",
  "interpretation": "Calibration recovers the parameters that generated the surface, and the recovery is read from a blind start -- the best of the 4 guesses that did not begin at the truth -- not from a start handed the answer. The four things the catalog keeps apart are kept apart here: the objective value, the surface fit (an implied-volatility RMSE of 1.75046e-11 and a price RMSE of 6.00191e-10 at the blind best), the parameter recovery (a normalised distance of 1.96729e-10 from the truth), and identifiability (whether other starts fit about as well from materially different parameters). 4 of 4 started fits converged.\n\nA low objective is never on its own read as success: a fit that matched the surface closely from the wrong parameters would be reported as a warning about identifiability, not a pass, and the materially-different fits that a low objective alone would hide are preserved in similar_fits.",
  "limitations": [
    "Parameter recovery is not uniform across the five parameters. On a surface of European prices, v0 and theta trade off against each other and kappa against xi, so the correlation and the variance level are recovered far more tightly than the mean reversion -- the per-parameter errors in best_blind.parameter_error show which.",
    "Recovery from a synthetic surface bounds the calibration's accuracy under the model's own assumptions. It says nothing about model error: a real surface is not generated by Heston, and a good synthetic recovery does not promise a good real-market fit.",
    "The verdict depends on the tolerances chosen (recovery_tolerance, fit_tolerance_iv_rmse) and on the guesses supplied. A different guess set could land in a different local minimum; the dispersion across starts and the non-uniqueness flag are the honest measure of how much that matters here."
  ],
